Relative to KEDIT's support of powerinput, the section "Notes for XEDIT
Users" in KEDIT's documentation states:
 "KEDIT has no Powerinput Mode.  However, entering Input Mode with
  INPUTMODE FULL and WORDWRAP ON provides an approximation of
  Powerinput Mode."

As for using the prefix area, when I use KEDIT I have the prefix area OFF.
I don't need it.  Many of the functions that are provided by the prefix
area in XEDIT are provided by key combinations in KEDIT.  For example,
to delete a line that the cursor is on, simple hit Alt-d (the alt key and
the letter d key).  With XEDIT, you'd have to move the cursor to the prefix
area, type a D, and hit enter.  To add a line after the line containing the
cursor, hit Alt-a.  Or similar to XEDIT's PF2, hit KEDIT's F2.

Want to duplicate a line that the cursor is on?  Hit Alt-=.

To copy (or move) a line that the cursor is on, hit Alt-l (which creates
to a one-line "line block").  Move the cursor to where ever you want to
copy (or move) the line and hit Alt-c (or Alt-m).

To operate on several lines at a time, define or mark a multi-line "line block"
by hitting alt-l with the cursor on one line.  Move the cursor to a second
line and hit Alt-l again.  (Try it, you'll see what I mean since the
block of lines is highlighted.)  As I showed above, I can use Alt-c or Alt-m
to copy or move the block.  (I can also use Alt-k to copy the block several
times.)  Use Alt-g (for "group delete") to delete the block.  If necessary,
use alt-u to "unmark" a block.

Of course, with KEDIT, these key combinations are available even when the
prefix area is on.  So you can use whichever method you're currently feel
comfortable with.  And, it you make a mistake, there's always UNDO.

